results.notes:
On Arroyo Willow (Salix lasiolepis). Abundant.

Thallus white, continuous, K+Y. Apothecia cleanly round, common, with a near black lightly pruinose disk and thick white thalline margin. Epihymenium dark (did I miss blue-black tints?), POL+ soluble in K immediately, hymenium and hypothecium hyaline, exciple with cortex seemingly thicker at base and with large POL+ crystals not soluble in K.

Spores hyaline, simple, ellipsoid. Average size 15.2×8.0 (n=6).

I need to take another run at this one to see if it is really a different taxon than other similar specimens identified as Lecanora meridionalis, (also with reservations…). See Observation 331796, Observation 308201.

Tubes: roughly .5 to 1 inch in length.
Odorless upon collection, but foul in age as often is the case with boletes.
Unable to get spores.
Seem to be able to eliminate most species except Rubroboletus and some members of the King bolete group.

results.notes:
Spores smooth, limoniform, thick-walled, both transparent and brown reddish in alkali.
Germ pore oblique in side view.
Measures for 30 spores broad view:
(9) 9.8 – 11.7 (12.3) × (6.8) 7.5 – 8.8 (9.5) µm

Pleurocystidia (sulphidia) present, cheliocystidia abundant and lamellae edge sterile, pileocystidia langeniform simetimes capitate, caulocystidia langeniform basidia 4 and 2 spored.

To my knowledge, given the latitude, only Panaeolus fimicola and Panaeolus ater are close to this description, I tend to name these mushrooms as Panaeolus ater, because spore size, presence of pleurocystidia.
- Panaeolus ater and Panaeolus fimicola are both condisered two distinct valid taxa both having pleurocystidia (facial cystidia sensu Ola’h) by Ola’h (Ola’h 1969), also Ola’h found in his experiments that Panaeolus ater is strong plsilocybin bearing mushroom, while Panaeolus fimicola is a latent psylocybin producer.
- In 1996 revision by Gerhardt Panaeolus ater is considered synonym of Panaeolus fimicola (Gerhardt 1996)
- Panaeolus fimicola is considered to not having pleurocystidia by Roy Watling (Watling & Gregory 1987)
- Francesco Doveri (Doveri 2004) considers Panaeolus fimicola and Panaeolus ater two distinct species with Panaeolus fimicola never having oblique germ pore and pleurocystidia (sulphidia), Panaeolus ater has both oblique germ pore.

NOTE on sulphidia: Despite the comodity of having at hand the coloring agent in the name, which is sulpho-vanillin, I like to call them pleurocystidia, I also call chrysocistidia pleurocystidia as well, because I think that any sterile appendicule growing on the gill side is sane to be called pleurocystidia, so that is why I consider “sulphidia” as subgenus Anellaria is today condisered in genus Panaeolus.

results.notes:
Growing terrestrially in mixed woods; mycelium white
Stipes: thick, about 2.5 × 2/3 inches; covered in a light lemon yellow wash after beginning white; interior partially solid and white but separable into vertical layers; shiny white vertical striations
Gills: purplish pink grapefruit color, a bit variable between specimens; gills and flesh unchanging/ not staining; I guess they could be free, but there appears to be tiny white teeth attaching each gill. The gills are very easily separated away from the apex, though
Pileus: conic and bright yellow, up to 2 cm broad; darkest at center where becoming a bit orange-tinted; cap margin always extends beyond the gills; colors of stipe and cap margin brown when “injured” or over time with age. The cap skin does not peel away easily from the gill edge. Flesh white.
Odor: not strongly scented; very weak and indistinct (maybe like crayon wax); perhaps slightly fungal over time, but that may have come from other specimens
Taste: farinaceous or cucumber-like and quite crunchy, with fungal aftertaste.

From the SVIMS PNW Tricholoma key, I get group 4 (no annulus or strong odor, yellow cap) and eventually end up with either davisiae or aestuans. Andrew Parker’s images of T. davisiae do look similar. I cannot find images of T. aestuans with gills of this color, but maybe that can happen. Both spp. have been recorded in Oregon.
